Czech discovery: a substance that also works on ‘stealed’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to block the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact prevails against the disadvantage that the compound on common virus variants does not work as strongly as one of the already existing drugs.
The disease of AIDS cannot be cured yet.
The patient can, however, prolong the lifespan of the drug and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral proliferation also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no medicines are more effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological College) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to cope with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metallocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the viral reproduction in a different way than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ‘enhanced’ compounds prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metallocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple cages consisting of bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
