The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-long animal ran on two strong back legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with silk claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then located in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the kinship relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began excavating the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for trias deposits, team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an exceptional finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current theory, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the eggs split into their three main developmental lines: the meat-eating theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor and also the birds, which were known as the "long-tailed" freurissaurus, and the four-legged orchiotides, the saurophans, and their verophans.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues to airbags, as well as the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, the respiration of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also possessed airbags and lightweight bones, it is likely that the common ancestor of the two groups had already brought about this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers conclude that the eggs first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all parts of the earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass as a supercontinent of Pangaea.
The team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are contradictions as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonner palaeontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could result, because in South America simply a particularly large number of primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptilian strain to the dominant landworms of the Middle Ages is still enigmatic.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and fly saurys, and with numerous other ostriches.
By the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the kinship at the border from the Trias to the Jura died out.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
But the success story didn’t last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite invasion of a group of animals bloomed, which had also evolved in the Triassic, and has since been enduring a shadow creature: the mammals.
