Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered vigilance consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in the aftermath.
The one-iroid state of consciousness occurs in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self-loss and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of state of boundary between dream and hallucination.
