75% of working mothers have problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 shows no doubt: 75% of employed women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited because of their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are big differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they exercise.
Those of them who do not perform any other activity outside the house, only work half-day, or do not have a fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
On the other hand, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sector, displace the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed-term employment receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after retiring, a figure that rises to 4.1 years for women with a fixed employment who have needed longer to achieve this and who have retired their first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on maternity, although less than the calendar in terms of the ability to conceive,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference could also be observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they have only a primary school or a higher education, were on average 25.1 or 32.1 mothers for the first time each.
In addition, there is another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with the main graduation get married before their first graduation and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school graduation make it very different and seek a graduation and then marry and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
