Sales of small trucks are rising again.
After almost two years, the car market for small cars finally begins to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles authorised in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6 per cent compared to 2008, and, more importantly, they are thus the first ever increase after 22 consecutive months with a steady decline, according to the pre-fabricated car association Anfac.
However, these good figures are currently only to be enjoyed with great caution, as the reference data used for comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly bad marketing year with a 60% decrease compared to the previous year.
However, it must be borne in mind that, apart from the increase in the last month, the total approvals of these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures of the previous financial year.
A total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold since January, but this number includes all the vehicles that make up the small car market: descendants of passenger cars, pick-ups, small cars, small trucks and lighter trucks.
