Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-block brake system at the time and as with the ESP stability control, the emergency braking aid systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly authorised passenger cars and lightweight small carriers, for the remaining vehicles a deadline for carriage has been set until the end of February 2011.
The adoption by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their way of working.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal by the brake force performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an inquiry commissioned by the Bosch component manufacturer for the vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not braked fully.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the brake system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car sets back during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via a radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while already exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver then reacts, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if needed.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the braking assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
