Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged to the workshops, where a reviewer has to assess the damage incurred and the cost of repair.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a long and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and hours of work, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of system.
The service and application providers for accident assessment and repair collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to process them thereafter and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera Group, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are created with its products.
The other two companies competing with the tool market for reviewing and reporting are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of whom makes the information available in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and motorizations have come to the market than in the total fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car arrives on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a difficult task, because each individual of the thousands of vehicles must be cataloged and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image, on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If it is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in one week if the procedure goes ahead quickly.
If it is a less conventional car, it can take up to three or four months. At present Audatex has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the vehicle fleet on the roads, it is more than 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audadex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialised in specific brands.
